Event delegation is a pattern where you attach **one listener on a parent element** instead of individual listeners on each child. The parent catches events from children via bubbling and uses `e.target` to determine which child was interacted with.

```javascript
// ONE listener handles ALL list items, even ones added later
document.querySelector("ul").addEventListener("click", (e) => {
    if (e.target.tagName === "LI") {
        console.log(`Clicked: ${e.target.textContent}`);
    }
});
```

**Why it's better:**
1. **Performance** — 1 listener instead of 100 (for 100 items)
2. **Dynamic elements** — works for elements added after page load
3. **Less memory** — fewer event listeners = less memory consumption
4. **Cleaner code** — one handler instead of loops setting up listeners

The **`input` event** fires on **every single change** to an input's value — every keystroke, paste, or deletion. It provides **real-time** feedback.

The **`change` event** fires only when the value is **committed** — for text inputs, this means when the user leaves the field (blur). For `<select>` and checkboxes, it fires immediately on change.

```javascript
// User types "Hello" in a text input:
// input fires: 5 times (H, e, l, l, o)
// change fires: 1 time (when user clicks away)
```

**Use `input`** for: live search filtering, character counters, real-time validation, password strength meters — anything needing instant feedback.

**Use `change`** for: dropdown selections, checkbox toggles, final value processing — when you only care about the end result.

By default, when a form is submitted, the browser **reloads the page** and sends the form data to the URL specified in the form's `action` attribute. This is the traditional server-side behavior.

With modern JavaScript, we want to handle form data **on the client side** — validate it, process it, or send it via `fetch()` to an API. If the page reloads, our JavaScript loses all its state and the user experience is disrupted.

```javascript
form.addEventListener("submit", (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();     // STOP the page reload
    // Now JavaScript handles everything
    const data = new FormData(form);
    // Validate, process, send via fetch(), etc.
});
```

**Without `e.preventDefault()`:** The page reloads instantly, the form data is lost (or sent to a non-existent server), any JavaScript state is destroyed, and the user sees a blank page or error.

```javascript
const list = document.querySelector("#task-list");

// ONE listener on the parent <ul>
list.addEventListener("click", (e) => {
    const item = e.target.closest("li");
    if (!item) return;
    if (!list.contains(item)) return;
    console.log(`Clicked: ${item.textContent}`);
    item.classList.toggle("completed");
});

// Adding a new item dynamically — it works WITHOUT adding a new listener!
const newItem = document.createElement("li");
newItem.textContent = "New Dynamic Task";
list.appendChild(newItem);
```

This works because: (1) The listener is on the `<ul>` parent. (2) When any `<li>` is clicked, the event bubbles up to `<ul>`. (3) `e.target.closest("li")` finds the actual `<li>` that was clicked. (4) New `<li>` elements automatically work because the listener is on the parent.
